We arrived close to 11:40 a.m. and thus they were serving lunch. The options were limited to three dishes plus fresh watermelon and cookies. they said that they would have more options once school starts on Monday. some of the students had complained that they were not getting very much food as they went through the line, but my experience was that we got exactly what we asked for even when we asked for a little extra of something like green beans. Right now you must be wearing a mask when you go in and you must remain at least 6 ft between yourself and the person in front of you. You go up and tell the person what you want in your to-go box and they serve it for you. Then you move to the next station to get your cookies and your drinks. If there are tables still available you can eat inside where you will find the tables are at least 8 ft apart. We chose to eat outside because, though it sounds extremely unlikely, it was actually not raining. There are a few picnic tables scattered around the campus near the dining center. We tried one of each of the three dishes that were available and the vegan wraps were the only one that had a lot of flavor. The chicken and swiss sandwiches were as bad as they looked in the display and the fish was very bland. The green beans and the tater tots were tasty.

Located literally across from the Gator Football Stadium. This place has a wide variety of food. From salad, pizza, burgers and fries, to ice cream, cereal, milk, soda and even pasta. The price is decent for what you get. It's all you can eat. Meaning you pay when you walk in and eat till you are full. There is WiFi and power outlets available as well as TV in most of the locations. There is also a quite room with tables and chairs if you don't want to watch TV and would rather talk or study. If you are out of class or at the stadium and would like something quick but don't want to walk very far this place is a good place to go. Check it out.

Tonight I ordered a Philly cheese steak. When it arrived, there was no bread in sight. You do the math. (Had to give the third star for the cookies, they're 8/10, would fill a to go box with them).  Edit: Today the TVs in one of the dining rooms was showing an R-Rated horror movie with extremely disturbing content. Not something I should even have to worry about seeing while having lunch. Unacceptable. Don't leave the TVs on inappropriate networks. Gore is not okay to show in a dining area, especially one that's open to the public.  Edit #2: After changing the type of foods I looked for here and beginning to see a small improvement in satisfaction, I had all hopes of quality improvement dashed, tonight, when I ate a burger full of bone fragments. Normally I wouldn't complain about one bad cut of meet at a place at which I eat almost daily, so I'm not doing that here either. In fact, this is at least the 5th burger (or other food item) that I've eaten here that contained non-food items. I'm sick of biting down to find a shock sent up my teeth because there is bone or something else in my food that shouldn't be there. It's a burger, it's literally the easiest fully cooked meal to make, and they cannot even make one that's fully edible. Much less can they make one that tastes good.

After attending the University of Florida my freshman year all I can say is WOW. There are so many flavors to choose from at the Gator Corner Dining Center. Whether your in the mood for some Asian sensation or some home cooked classics, this is the place for you. Although I must say, this place would be nothing without Garrett's sandwiches made from handpicked ingredients and perfectly toasted pieces of whole grain bread. Not only is the salad bar exquisite, but they also offer some of the finest pastries in all of Gainesville. I highly recommend the cookie sandwich, two chocolate chip cookies with any flavor of ice cream you want in the middle. Gator Dining has not disappointed me yet. If I could stay a fifth year or do graduate work at the University I would eat here all day every day.
